Tidal Zone-based SWOs validation

Hao Zhang

January 17, 2017

Objectives

Discretize the tide peak shift using the regulator SWOs water level along the Delaware River and the Schuylkill River by each Tidal Zone.

Results

The SWOs water level time-series between July 22, 2016 and July 28, 2016 were extracted from the Telog server. There was 1.60 in of rainfall on July 25, 2016. The zonal-adjusted time series (hourly) at the coast guard station is overlaid on each plot as dots.

The curves can be smoothed by changing the rollPeriod at the left-bottom corner of each plot, the ZN series would be affected though.

Conclusions

SWOs on the Delaware River showed more delayed peaks at upstream regulators, the time shift can be as much as 30 minutes.
Bottomline: 3 tidal zones are able to represent the pattern variants on Delaware.
SWOs on the Schuylkill River do not show significant peak shift. In general, the peaks of SWOs on the Schuylkill is about 15 minutes ahead of the peak on Delaware.
Bottomline: the single tidal zone (ZN0) is representative for all Schuylkill regulators.
